@Node "XarWhy()" "xpkarchive.library/XarWhy"

@{b}    NAME@{ub}
        XarWhy()

@{b}    SYNOPSIS@{ub}

        errortext = XarWhy( arc , errcode)
           D0                A0     D0

        UBYTE *XarWhy(XarHandle *, LONG)

@{b}    FUNCTION@{ub}

        Returns a pointer to a descriptive text for the last error that
        appeared in this archive, if arc is not NULL.
        If arc is NULL, then you get a description for the errcode.

        'errcode' is ignored, if arc is not NULL.


@{b}    INPUT@{ub}

        arc - XarHandle of the archive
        errcode - Error code


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}

        The same error-code may result in different error-descriptions
        every time you call this function! E.g. a filename might be
        contained in the error-description.


@{b}    RESULT@{ub}

        Pointer to the error-description. (Read only !!!!)


@{b}    SEE ALSO@{ub}

@EndNode

@Node "--tags--()" "xpkarchive.library/--tags--"

@{b}    Tags for XarOpenArchiveA()@{ub}

        XAR_ArchiveName  (UBYTE *)
            Name of the file of the archive.

        XAR_ArchiveMode (ULONG)
           There are three modes to open an archive:
                XAR_ModeOldArchive:
                    Only existing archives will be opened. If it
                    does not exist @{"XarOpenArchiveA()" Link "XarOpenArchiveA()"} will fail. This is
                    the default mode.
                XAR_ModeNewArchive:
                    Existing files will be deleted and a new, empty
                    archive will be created.
                XAR_ModeAppen:
                    Creates an archive if none exists and opens the
                    archive if one exists.




@{b}    Tags for all functions requiring tags except XarOpenArchiveA():@{ub}

        XAR_ArcLock (XarLock *)
            Arclock of the file.

        XAR_Archive (XarHandle *)
            Archandle of the archive.

        XAR_FileIndex (ULONG)
            Index of the file in the archive. This tag is only valid if
            there is also XAR_Archive given.

        XAR_FileName (UBYTE *)
            Filename of the file in the archive. This tag is only valid if
            there is also XAR_Archive given. The default generation
            is 0 unless you change the generation with the tag:

        XAR_Generation (ULONG)
            Generationnumber of the file in the archive.


          For identifying file in the archive use one of the following:
             - XAR_ArcLock
          or - XAR_Archive + XAR_FileIndex
          or - XAR_Archive + XAR_FileName  [ + XAR_Generation (default: 0)]

@{b}    NOTE: the combination of XAR_Filename and XAR_Generation is ambigous when@{ub}
          there is more than one file with the same filename and generation-
          number in the archive. In this case it identifies the first file
          in the archive that matches the filename and generationnumber.


@{b}    Additional Tags for XarAddFileA():@{ub}

        XAR_Archive (XarHandle *) |
        XAR_FileName (UBYTE *)    | s.a.
        XAR_Generation (ULONG)    |

        XAR_FileNote (UBYTE *)
            Filenote for the file to be added.
            (May not be supported by all archive-types)

        XAR_CRC   (USHORT)
            16-bit CRC-value
            (May not be supported by all archive-types)

        XAR_CRC32 (ULONG) (V2)
            32-bit CRC-value
            (May not be supported by all archive-types)

        XAR_Protection (ULONG)
            Protectionflags of the file

        XAR_AutoNextGen (BOOLEAN)
            Call XarNextGeneration if 1,which is the default value.
            If you supply 0 then XarNextGeneration is not called. This may
            result in duplicate files with the same generationnumber in the
            archive.
            IMPORTANT: You must not use other values than 0 or 1,
            since it might be that there are other values with other
            functionality in the future.
            (May not be supported by all archive-types in this form)

        XAR_TimeDay   (UBYTE)   | relative to 1.1.1900 which is:
        XAR_TimeMonth (UBYTE)   | Day: 1   Month:1   Year: 0
        XAR_TimeYear  (UBYTE)   |

        XAR_TimeHour  (UBYTE)   |
        XAR_TimeMin   (UBYTE)   |
        XAR_TimeSec   (UBYTE)   |

        XAR_DateStamp (struct @{"DateStamp" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:dos/dos.h/Main" 53} *)
            These tags are used to specify the time for XarAddFile() as
            day, month, year, hour, minute and second or using a datestamp.
            The default behaviour is to use the date and time of the file,
            or in the case of XPK_InBuf or XPK_InHook the actual time.
            This time can be altered using the above tags.

            These tags are also used to modify the FileData using
            XarModifyFileData().

        XAR_CurrentTime (BOOLEAN)
            Use the current time instead of the date and time of the file.




@{b}    Additional Tags for XarRenameFileA()@{ub}

        XAR_NewName (UBYTE *)
            The new filename for the file.

        XAR_NewGeneration (UBYTE)
            The new generationnumber for the file.

        XAR_AutoNextGen (ULONG)
            Call XarNextGeneration if 1,which is the default value.
            If you supply 0 then XarNextGeneration is not called. This may
            result in duplicate files with the same generationnumber in the
            archive.
            IMPORTANT: You must not use other values than 0 or 1,
            since it might be that there are other values with other
            functionality in the future.
            (May not be supported by all archive-types in this form)


@{b}    Additional tags for XarSetFileNoteA()@{ub}

        XAR_FileNote (UBYTE *)
            Filenote for the file. In the archive the filenotes have no
            limited size, but remember that it is not possible to extract
            the complete filenote, if it is longer than 80 bytes with
            most current filesystems.
            (May not be supported by all archive-types)


@{b}    Additional tags for XarCopyFileA()@{ub}

        XAR_DestArchive (XarHandle *)
            ArcHandle of the destination archive.

        XAR_AutoNextGen (ULONG)
            (see above)

        XAR_NewName (UBYTE *)
            New name for the file in the dest. archive,
            default: use old name

        XAR_NewGeneration (UBYTE)
            New generationnumber for the file in the dest. archive,
            default: use old generationnumber

        XAR_FileNote (UBYTE *)
            New filenote, default: use old filenote


@{b}    Additional tags for @{"XarModifyFileDataA()" Link "XarModifyFileDataA()"} and XarAddFileA()@{ub}

        XAR_CRC  (USHORT)
            CRC checksums of the file in the archive. CRC checksums are not
            supportet by the xpkmaster.library yet. Therefore archives
            created with xpk-compression-methods do not have a valid
            CRC-checksum (Type: "XPKArchive"). However XAR-sublibs may
            support this value.


        XAR_CRC32  (ULONG) (V2)
            CRC checksums of the file in the archive. CRC checksums are not
            supportet by the xpkmaster.library yet. Therefore archives
            created with xpk-compression-methods do not have a valid
            CRC-checksum (Type: "XPKArchive"). However XAR-sublibs may
            support this value.


        XAR_Protection (ULONG)
            Protection of the file.

        XAR_AutoNextGen (ULONG)
            (see above)


@{b}    Additional tags for XarOpenArchiveA()@{ub}

        XAR_ArchiveMode (ULONG)
            Mode of opening the archive. There are three modes to open the
            archive:

                XAR_ModeOldArchive:
                    Only existing archives will be opened. If it does not
                    exist @{"XarOpenArchiveA()" Link "XarOpenArchiveA()"} will fail. This is the default
                    mode.

                XAR_ModeNewArchive:
                    Existing files will be deleted and a new, empty archive
                    will be created.

                XAR_ModeAppend:
                    Creates an archive if none exists and opens the archive
                    if one exists.

        XAR_ShowDirs (BOOLEAN) (V2)
            Select if empty directories should be hidden away (default TRUE).


@{b}    Global tags for all functions@{ub}

        XAR_Error (LONG *)
            Pointer to an error variable. The error code is stored in this
            variable on failure. Error codes <0 are error codes of the
            xpkmaster.library (see xpk.h), error codes >0 are from the
            xpkarchive.library.
        IMPORTANT NOTE:
            Only error-codes >=XARERROR_LEVEL are real errors. The other
            codes are just informational or warnings. See also --Error--


@{b}    Input / Output tags:@{ub}

        The normal xpk-tags from xpkmaster.library are used as input/output
        tags. Be aware that you must not supply ouput tags to @{"XarAddFileA()" Link "XarAddFileA()"}
        and no input tags to @{"XarExtractFileA()" Link "XarExtractFileA()"}.

        From version 2.0 of the include-file, there are now defines, which
        map them on the XPK-equivalents:


@{b}    THE INPUT TAGS. One of the four must be present for XarAddFileA()@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_InName (=XPK_InName)  (char *)@{ub}
        Name of file to compress. On packing, XPK_InLen can be
        specified in order to pack only the first N bytes.

@{b}    XAR_InFH (=XPK_InFH)    (BPTR)@{ub}
        File handle to compress from. It is not necessary that
        the handle is at the beginning of the file. Otherwise same
        rules as in XPK_InName apply.

@{b}    XAR_InBuf (=XPK_InBuf)   (UBYTE *)@{ub}
        Memory block to compress. If you use this one, you
        have to specify InLen as well.

@{b}    XAR_InHook (=XPK_InHook)  (struct @{"Hook" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:utility/hooks.h/Main" 23} *)@{ub}
        Hookfunc to deliver data for compression. Must also supply XPK_InLen.
        (Actually I have no information about that one and therefore it
         is not fully supported.)



@{b}     IN ADDITION@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_InLen (=XPK_InLen)   (LONG)@{ub}
        Specifies the number of bytes to read when compressing.
        ignored on decompression.


@{b}     THE OUTPUT TAGS. One of the five must be present for XarExtractFileA()@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_OutName (=XPK_OutName)      (char *)@{ub}
        Name of file to write decompressed data to.

@{b}    XAR_OutFH (=XPK_OutFH)       (BPTR)@{ub}
        File handle to append decompressed data to.

@{b}    XAR_OutBuf (=XPK_OutBuf)       (APTR)@{ub}
        The memory block to write decompressed data to. Must also
        supply XPK_OutBufLen. It needs to be outlen+XPK_MARGIN. Use
        @{"XarGetFileData()" Link "XarGetFileData()"} to find out outlen. Note that this buffer must
        be word aligned.

@{b}    XAR_GetOutBuf (=XPK_GetOutBuf)    (APTR *)@{ub}
        Allocates a block of appropriate size and stores a pointer to
        it in the variable pointed to by ti_Data. Must also supply
        XAR_GetOutBufLen plus XAR_GetOutLen and can XPK_OutMemType.

@{b}    XAR_OutHook (=XPK_OutHook)     (struct @{"Hook" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:utility/hooks.h/Main" 23} *)@{ub}
        Hookfunc to accept (de)compressed data. See special chapter
        on I/O hook functions.

@{b}     IN ADDITION@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_OutBufLen (=XPK_OutBufLen)   (LONG)@{ub}
        The length of the output buffer you supply using XAR_OutBuf.
        For decompression, must be decompressed size (see @{"XarGetFileData()" Link "XarGetFileData()"})
        plus XPK_MARGIN.

@{b}    XAR_GetOutLen (=XPK_GetOutLen)   (LONG *)@{ub}
        Stores the total length of the decompressed data in the variable
        pointed to by ti_Data. Note: V2 of xpkmaster required for correct
        operation on compression.

@{b}    XAR_GetOutBufLen (=XPK_GetOutBufLen) (LONG *)@{ub}
        Stores the length of the buffer allocated for the data in the
        variable pointed to by ti_Data. @{"FreeMem()" Link "exec/FreeMem()"} the buffer you  get
        from XAR_GetOutBuf with the length you get from XAR_GetOutBufLen.
        Note: For the number of bytes written, refer to XAR_GetOutLen!

@{b}    XAR_OutMemType  (=XPK_OutMemType) (LONG)@{ub}
        The type of memory to use for the output buffer.


@{b}     PACKING TAGS@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_PackMethod (=XPK_PackMethod)  (char *)@{ub}
        Use indicated method for packing. This would be a four
        letter string in most cases, plus an optional dot and
        a packing mode. See XAR_PackMode

@{b}    XAR_PackMode  (=XPK_PackMode)   (LONG)@{ub}
        Packing mode for sublib to use. Range is 0...100, where 100 is
        most efficient.

@{b}    XPK_StepDown and XPK_ChunkSize are not fully supported and may be@{ub}
        ignored



@{b}     OTHER TAGS@{ub}

@{b}    XAR_ProgressHook (=XPK_ChunkHook)    (struct @{"Hook" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:utility/hooks.h/Main" 23} *)@{ub}
       @{"Hook" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:utility/hooks.h/Main" 23} function to call between chunks. Can print a progress
       report, and if it returns a nonzero value, the (de)compression
       will be aborted. See special chapter on progress functions.


@EndNode

@Node "--error--()" "xpkarchive.library/--error--"

@{b}    Some notes about the error codes:@{ub}

@{b}    The xpkarchive.library has four levels of error codes:@{ub}

        - Informational codes: These are no errors at all.

            XARINF_NEW_ARCHIVE:     A new archive has been created.
            XARINF_NOT_EXCLUSIVE:   The archivefile could not be opened for
                                    exclusive access. This will lead to
                                    corrupted archives, if an archive is
                                    opened more than once and data is
                                    written to it.
                                    For V36 or higher the archive is opened
                                    using an exclusive Lock and
                                    OpenFromLock();
            XARINF_ARCHIVE_CORRUPT: There are more or less harmless errors
                                    in the archive.

        - Warning codes (code>=XARWARNING_LEVEL): They give you a warning
            that there is something wrong with the archive.

            XARWARN_ARCHIVE_CORRUPT: There is a serious error in the
                archive. Therefore it is not possible to add any files to
                the archive any more. If you try it you will get the error
                code XARERR_ARCHIVE_CORRUPT. You can still try to extract
                files from the archive.

            For the other codes read xpkarchive.h

        - Error codes (code>=XARERROR_LEVEL): Real error codes


        - @{"Custom" Link "TEXT_INCLUDE:hardware/custom.h/Main" 26} error codes (code>=XARCUSTOM_LEVEL) that are generated by
          XAR-sublibs.

@{b}    You can get a description of the error by using XarWhy().@{ub}


@{b}    NOTE@{ub}
         XAR-sublibs may not support some functions, then they
         will return XARERR_FUNCTION_NOT_SUPPORTED.


@EndNode

@Node "--generations--()" "xpkarchive.library/--generations--"

@{b}   Unlike most formats of other archivers the file-format that is used by@{ub}
@{b}   the xpkarchive.library supports having different versions of one file@{ub}
@{b}   with the same filename in one archive. Therefore this file-format@{ub}
@{b}   supports generations of files, which identify different versions of the@{ub}
@{b}   file. The higher the generationnumber the newer is the file. Since it is@{ub}
@{b}   always possible to modify the generationnumber by the programmer it may@{ub}
@{b}   occur that there are files with the same filename and generation.@{ub}
   (although this case should be avoided) It is the job of the programmer to
@{b}   prevent duplicate generationnumbers of one file.@{ub}


@{b}   NOTES@{ub}

    - The numbering scheme for generations has been changed for version 2.0.
      In former versions a lower generationnumber indicated a newer file,
      now newer files get higher generationnumbers.

    - Now the versionnumbers are within the range from 0 to 65535, whereas
      they used to be in the range from 0 to 255.

    - The generationnumber XAR_FileNewest (=0) always specifies the newest
      file with a filename in the archive.

    - Deleted files are not marked by the generationnumber any more.

@EndNode

@Node "--progress--()" "xpkarchive.library/--progress--"

@{b}    THE PROGRESS REPORT HOOK@{ub}

@{b}   The progress report function is a standard hook function that will@{ub}
@{b}   be called after every chunk (de)compressed. This will be about@{ub}
@{b}   every 30K, or just twice if the file format is not split in chunks.@{ub}
@{b}   If the field h_Entry in the hook is set, it will be called with@{ub}
@{b}   the hook itself in a0 and the progress report structure in a1.@{ub}
@{b}   If your compiler does not support direct calling in registers,@{ub}
@{b}   it must have a library function that puts the arguments that@{ub}
@{b}   puts the arguments wherever the functions needs them and call it.@{ub}
@{b}   A4 is guaranteed to be saved so it is not necessary to provide@{ub}
@{b}   geta4() or __saveds in C programs. If the progress report function@{ub}
@{b}   returns a nonzero value, (de)compression aborts.  Note: it is YOUR@{ub}
@{b}   responsibility to turn off your compiler's CTRL-C-handling e.g. if@{ub}
@{b}   you do printf()s in the chunk function!@{ub}

@{b}    THE PROGRESS REPORT STRUCTURE@{ub}

@{b}   LONG   Type      : XPKPROG_START, XPKPROG_MID or XPKPROG_END@{ub}
@{b}   STRPTR   PackerName   : Brief name of packer being used@{ub}
@{b}   STRPTR   PackerLongName   : Descriptive name of packer being used@{ub}
@{b}   STRPTR   Activity   : Packing/unpacking message@{ub}
@{b}   STRPTR   FileName   : Name of file being processed, if available@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   CCur      : Amount of packed data already processed@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   UCur      : Amount of unpacked data already processed@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   ULen      : Amount of unpacked data in file@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   CF      : Compression factor so far@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   Done      : Percentage done already@{ub}
@{b}   LONG   Speed      : Bytes per second, from beginning of stream@{ub}


@{b}   NOTE:@{ub}

@{b}   The progress-hook gets also called for directories. This case is@{ub}
@{b}   indicated by ULen=-1 and it the following is true:@{ub}

      Speed=0;
      CCur=0
      UCur=0
      CF=0
      Done=100


@EndNode

@Node "--BUGS--" "xpkarchive.library/--BUGS--"

@{b}   The xpkarchive.library does not support the tags TAG_MORE and TAG_SKIP@{ub}
@{b}   yet.@{ub}

@EndNode

@Node "--general--()" "xpkarchive.library/--general--"


@{b}    SOME GENERAL NOTES@{ub}

        Some notes about the file-list, whose entries can be accessed via
        @{"XarGetLock()" Link "XarGetLock()"}, @{"XarNextLock()" Link "XarNextLock()"} and XarPrevLock():

        -  The order of the files in the archive does not change, except
           that an 'arclock' may be removed from the list when a file gets
           deleted.

        -  New files are added to the end of the file-list.


        If you delete a file and want to check if the arclock is still
        valid you can do something like this:


        XarLock arclock,prevlock;
        int valid=FALSE;

        if(prevlock=XarPrevLock(arc)) {
            XarDeleteFile(arclock);
            if(XarNextLock(prevlock)==arclock) valid=TRUE;
        } else {
            XarDeleteFile(arclock);
            if(XarNextLock(prevlock)==XarGetLock(arc)) valid=TRUE;
        }
@EndNode

